  "prompt": "What integer solutions to x and y are there for 167x+113y=1?",
  "response": "To find integer solutions to the equation 167x + 113y = 1, we can use the Euclidean Algorithm.\nFirst, we apply the Euclidean Algorithm to find the greatest common divisor (GCD) of 167 and 113:\n\\begin{align*} 167 &= 1 \\cdot 113 + 54 \\\\ 113 &= 2 \\cdot 54 + 5 \\\\ 54 &= 10 \\cdot 5 + 4 \\\\ 5 &= 1 \\cdot 4 + 1 \\end{align*}\nThe GCD is 1, so there are integer solutions. Now we can work backward to express 1 as a linear combination of 167 and 113:\n\\begin{align*} 1 &= 5 - 1 \\cdot 4 \\\\ 1 &= 5 - 1 (54 - 10 \\cdot 5) \\\\ 1 &= 5 - 54 + 10 \\cdot 5 \\\\ 1 &= 11 \\cdot 5 - 54 \\\\ 1 &= 11 (113 - 2 \\cdot 54) - 54 \\\\ 1 &= 11 \\cdot 113 - 22 \\cdot 54 - 54 \\\\ 1 &= 11 \\cdot 113 - 23 \\cdot 54 \\\\ 1 &= 11 \\cdot 113 - 23 (167 - 1 \\cdot 113) \\\\ 1 &= 11 \\cdot 113 - 23 \\cdot 167 + 23 \\cdot 113 \\\\ 1 &= 34 \\cdot 113 - 23 \\cdot 167 \\\\ 1 &= -23 \\cdot 167 + 34 \\cdot 113 \\end{align*}\nSo, we have 1 = -23(167) + 34(113). Thus, x = -23 and y = 34 is one solution to the equation 167x + 113y = 1.\nNow we want to find all integer solutions. Let $x_0 = -23$ and $y_0 = 34$. Then the general solution is given by\n$$ x = x_0 + \\frac{113}{1} k = -23 + 113k $$\n$$ y = y_0 - \\frac{167}{1} k = 34 - 167k $$\nwhere k is an integer.\nWe can check this solution:\n$$ 167(-23+113k) + 113(34-167k) = 167(-23) + 167(113k) + 113(34) - 113(167k) = -3841 + 18871k + 3842 - 18871k = 1 $$\nThus, the general solution is given by x = -23 + 113k and y = 34 - 167k, where k is an integer.\n\nFinal Answer: The final answer is $\\boxed{x=-23, y=34}$",
